I believe [the {{BuildInfo.VersionAtLeast()}} function|https://github.com/go-mgo/mgo/blob/9aff4bc9b9b01ee9a239435335448ee1af7062a5/session.go#L4256-L4266] should also be considering each version value's significance, such that:

{code}
bi := &BuildInfo{VersionArray: []int{3,2,1,0}}
bi.VersionAtLeast(2,5,5) == true
{code}

Currently {{bi.VersionAtLeast(2,5,5)}} returns false. 

The {{else if}} clause added below would appear to provide (what I believe to be) the expected behavior:

{code:golang}
func (bi *BuildInfo) VersionAtLeast(version ...int) bool {
	for i := range version {
		if i == len(bi.VersionArray) {
			return false
		}
		if bi.VersionArray[i] < version[i] {
			return false
		} else if bi.VersionArray[i] > version[i] {
			return true
		}
                // else equal, so continue to next version array value
	}
	return true
}
{code}

Go playground with some micro "test cases":
https://play.golang.org/p/pxUSLTTq7-

While profiling a small program that runs commands that accepts the result into a {{bson.Raw}}, I noticed that the command path appears to {{bson.Unmarshal}} once into my {{bson.Raw}} argument, however then a second time into a locally declared {{bson.M}} for a {{debugf}} message.

https://github.com/go-mgo/mgo/blob/b6e2fa371e64216a45e61072a96d4e3859f169da/session.go#L3205-L3206

Snippet
{code}
	if result != nil {
		err = bson.Unmarshal(data, result)
		if err == nil {
			var res bson.M 
			bson.Unmarshal(data, &res) // <= Additional Unmarshal
			debugf("Run command unmarshaled: %#v, result: %#v", op, res)
		} else {
			debugf("Run command unmarshaling failed: %#v", op, err)
			return err
		}
	}
{code}

I'm assuming the double decoding is on accident as I also notice that other paths, such as through {{One(result)}} and {{Next(result)}}, their {{debugf()}} messages log the result structure provided by the user.

Running {{bson.UnmarshalJSON}} on a string such as 
{code}
{"foo" : 123}
{code}
causes a panic. This is due to the space between the key {{"foo"}} and the colon symbol. The source of the bug can be traced to here: https://github.com/10gen/mgo/blob/v2/internal/json/decode.go#L1044

The {{unquote}} function is passed the byte array {{name}}, which does not have whitespace trimmed.

Breaking change. Implementing this API for Motor was a mistake:
{code}
@gen.coroutine                                            
def fifth_item():                                         
    yield collection.insert([{'i': i} for i in range(10)])
    cursor = collection.find().sort([('i', 1)])[5]        
    yield cursor.fetch_next                               
    doc = cursor.next_object()                            
{code}
Require users to set skip and limit longhand:
{code}
@gen.coroutine
def fifth_item():
    yield collection.insert([{'i': i} for i in range(10)])
    cursor = collection.find().sort([('i', 1)]).skip(5).limit(1)
    yield cursor.fetch_next
    doc = cursor.next_object()
    print(doc['i'])
 
IOLoop.current().run_sync(fifth_item)
{code}

The following is *not* the right way to iterate a MotorCursor:
{code}
for doc in cursor:
    pass
{code}
Motor should throw TypeError: MotorCursor object is not iterable. Instead, "doc" is bound to the cursor itself and the loop runs forever.

This is because, to my surprise, a Python object *without* an \_\_iter\_\_ is still iterable if it implements \_\_getitem\_\_. The for-loop first calls:
{code}
MotorCursor.__getitem__(0)
{code}
...which updates the delegate Cursor's skip and limit and returns the original MotorCursor. Hence the infinite loop.

It's probably best to delete \_\_getitem\_\_ and require you to use skip() and limit() instead; implementing \_\_getitem\_\_ falsely implies that a MotorCursor is iterable by conventional methods.
